But 10 years, people will look at some ridiculous missing links and ask, “What were they thinking? There’s no connection to the train station and they could have included it by losing these 15 parking spots!” And maybe it will get built then… but probably not.

In 10 years, my current neighborhood will be pretty good for bicycling for some of those 1-3 mile trips, but far less than it could have been with planners and developers who saw and believed in what was possible.
To anyone who doubts me, I gesture dismissively at Arlington VA, which builds for people and their cars, along with a bunch of overpriced new Metro entrances.

Once you build denser cities with driving OK, all you’ve done is generated new neighbors to oppose taking the space needed to build your network. 

Plan it from the start, bring in new neighbors who know that driving isn’t the default, rebuild public space with development.
